WEBVTT

00:01.068 --> 00:02.935
Dre:<i> It's a big world.</i>

00:02.937 --> 00:05.504
<i>And from place to place,
it's pretty different.</i>

00:05.506 --> 00:08.007
[ Marvin Gaye's "Inner City Blues" plays
] <i>But no matter where we're from,</i>

00:08.009 --> 00:11.276
<i>the experiences, conversations,
and images we see</i>

00:11.278 --> 00:12.878
<i>have an effect on us.</i>

00:12.880 --> 00:15.314
<i>They make us curious.</i>

00:15.316 --> 00:18.817
<i>As a child, it's only natural
that that curiosity</i>

00:18.819 --> 00:22.221
<i>makes us question
what's going on in the world.</i>

00:22.223 --> 00:24.123
<i>So we bring those questions,</i>

00:24.125 --> 00:27.226
<i>some of them hard questions,
to our parents.</i>

00:27.228 --> 00:30.896
<i>As a parent, dealing
with those hard questions</i>

00:30.898 --> 00:32.831
<i>used to be a lot easier.</i>

00:32.833 --> 00:34.733
Turn the damn TV off, boy.

00:34.735 --> 00:37.002
♪ Yeah, me wanna holler ♪
<i>But now, things have changed.</i>

00:37.004 --> 00:40.739
<i>Between gossip blogs,
the Internet, and 24-hour news,</i>

00:40.741 --> 00:44.510
<i>it's become impossible to
control what our kids see.</i>

00:44.512 --> 00:45.911
<i>And they're naturally curious.</i>

00:45.913 --> 00:49.748
♪ Trigger-happy policing ♪

00:49.750 --> 00:52.084
<i>So at some point,
whether we like it or not,</i>

00:52.086 --> 00:54.019
<i>our kids are going
to ask questions</i>

00:54.021 --> 00:56.555
<i>that we have to answer.</i>

00:56.557 --> 00:58.657
Why are these people so mad?

00:58.659 --> 01:01.560
♪ Ohh, make me want to holler ♪

01:01.562 --> 01:04.496
♪ The way they do my life ♪

01:04.498 --> 01:06.565
♪ Yeah, make me want to holler ♪

01:06.567 --> 01:08.567
♪ The way they do my life ♪

01:08.569 --> 01:09.635
♪ Ohh, yeah ♪

01:16.377 --> 01:18.777
Because the police
are damn thugs.

01:18.779 --> 01:20.512
Not all police.

01:20.514 --> 01:22.081
Yeah, only 92%.

01:22.083 --> 01:25.350
The other 8% are advisors
on "Law & Order" episodes.

01:25.352 --> 01:26.418
Okay!

01:26.420 --> 01:28.954
Guys, why don't you
go to the kitchen,

01:28.956 --> 01:31.056
get some to-go menus,
and see if you can

01:31.058 --> 01:33.525
find us something good
to have for dinner tonight.

01:33.527 --> 01:34.693
Why even bother?

01:34.695 --> 01:36.295
We're just gonna end up
at Chipotle again.

01:36.297 --> 01:37.596
We cannot let that happen.

01:37.598 --> 01:39.465
Well, why don't you go find
something good, then?

01:39.467 --> 01:40.933
[ Sighs ]
See what we can find, huh?

01:40.935 --> 01:42.367
Thank you.

01:42.369 --> 01:44.970
You know, you can try and mask
the problems of this world

01:44.972 --> 01:47.873
in savory barbacoa meat
and floury tortillas

01:47.875 --> 01:51.276
if you choose, Rainbow,
but it doesn't change the fact

01:51.278 --> 01:54.980
the police in this country
have a problem with Black folks.

01:54.982 --> 01:56.381
Thank you, Mama.

01:56.383 --> 01:58.383
It's a little more nuanced
than that, Dad.

01:58.385 --> 01:59.485
Thank you, Junior.

01:59.487 --> 02:03.155
I can't wait until a cop
gets a hold of your ass.

02:03.157 --> 02:05.824
Police definitely
have a place in society,

02:05.826 --> 02:08.760
but with almost
1,000 police-related fatalities

02:08.762 --> 02:09.928
and billions of dollars

02:09.930 --> 02:11.663
in misconduct settlements...
Mm-hmm. Mm-hmm.

02:11.665 --> 02:12.965
There might be some issues.

02:12.967 --> 02:14.933
Boom! That's my boy.

02:14.935 --> 02:16.468
Ha-ha!
I taught him that.

02:16.470 --> 02:17.603
What?

02:17.605 --> 02:18.904
[ All grumbling ]
No, you didn't.

02:18.906 --> 02:21.773
I got most of what I learned
from Ta-Nehisi Coates.

02:21.775 --> 02:23.308
Well, he probably
got it from me.

02:23.310 --> 02:25.010
Just because
I didn't write it down...

02:25.012 --> 02:26.612
Or say it out loud.

02:26.614 --> 02:27.946
Or ever think it.

02:27.948 --> 02:29.481
What's going on?

02:29.483 --> 02:31.250
Oh, they're about to say
whether there's gonna be

02:31.252 --> 02:32.751
an indictment in
the McQuillan case.

02:32.753 --> 02:34.086
Oh, I think I heard about that.

02:34.088 --> 02:35.988
What do you mean,
you<i> think</i> you heard about that?

02:35.990 --> 02:37.089
It's been all over the news.

02:37.091 --> 02:38.457
It's the one where
they shot the kid

02:38.459 --> 02:39.658
in the middle
of the street, right?

02:39.660 --> 02:40.659
Mnh-mnh, mnh-mnh.

02:40.661 --> 02:41.994
That was Chicago.

02:41.996 --> 02:43.362
Oh, is this the guy
that got shot

02:43.364 --> 02:45.097
in front of the college
at the traffic stop?

02:45.099 --> 02:46.198
No, that was Charleston.

02:46.200 --> 02:47.666
Charleston?
No, Charleston was

02:47.668 --> 02:49.601
the unarmed guy who got shot
in the back.

02:49.603 --> 02:51.370
Cincy was the traffic stop.
Oh, yeah.

02:51.372 --> 02:52.671
Well, wait,
then what was New York?

02:52.673 --> 02:55.107
Oh, New York was the unarmed guy
who was selling cigarettes

02:55.109 --> 02:56.275
that got choked.
Cigarettes!

02:56.277 --> 02:58.544
Yeah, this is the unarmed guy
who was selling DVDs

02:58.546 --> 03:00.445
that got tased 37 times.

03:00.447 --> 03:01.780
Wow.
Is he okay?

03:01.782 --> 03:05.851
He got tased 37 times,
so, you know, he's not great.

03:05.853 --> 03:07.486
Mm.
And I'm not in any way saying

03:07.488 --> 03:09.621
that this justifies what
happened, but I think

03:09.623 --> 03:12.024
it's important that you know
the only two movie titles

03:12.026 --> 03:14.726
that he had were "Trainwreck"
and "Chi-Raq," so...

03:14.728 --> 03:16.662
Oh, my God,
I loved "Trainwreck."

03:16.664 --> 03:17.563
Loved?

03:17.565 --> 03:18.730
Are you kidding me?

03:18.732 --> 03:20.232
That Marv Albert scene?

03:20.234 --> 03:21.166
So funny, right?
Crazy.

03:21.168 --> 03:23.001
What movie was that from?

03:23.003 --> 03:25.137
Well first, LeBron was... And don't
even get me started on the plot holes.

03:25.139 --> 03:26.738
Would you two shut up?!

03:26.740 --> 03:28.473
Thank you!

03:28.475 --> 03:31.143
"Chi-Raq" is clearly
the reason the boy was tased.

03:31.145 --> 03:32.744
Ruby!
Horrible movie.

03:32.746 --> 03:33.812
[ Laughs ] Just awful.

03:33.814 --> 03:34.713
Come on, now.

03:34.715 --> 03:36.081
Zoey: All right, then.

03:36.083 --> 03:38.584
Well, I will be in my room,
doing my Spanish homework

03:38.586 --> 03:40.385
before my teacher tases me.

03:40.387 --> 03:43.155
What? Excuse me, baby.
That is not funny.

03:43.157 --> 03:44.089
And no.

03:44.091 --> 03:45.357
This is important.

03:45.359 --> 03:48.360
We're all going to sit
and watch it together.

03:48.362 --> 03:49.428
Dad, I don't...
Ah, ah, ah!

03:49.430 --> 03:51.263
Sit down!
Okay.

03:51.265 --> 03:52.998
Lemon: <i>So with accusations
of officer misconduct</i>

03:53.000 --> 03:54.566
<i>rising from coast to coast,</i>

03:54.568 --> 03:57.236
<i>crowds around the country are
tensely awaiting the decision</i>

03:57.238 --> 03:58.604
<i>regarding an indictment.</i>

03:58.606 --> 04:01.340
Is anyone gonna explain
to us what's happening?

04:01.342 --> 04:03.275
Uh, hey, you got to keep
looking through those menus.

04:03.277 --> 04:04.443
Are you done? No.
Okay.

04:04.445 --> 04:05.944
Hey, Dre, can I talk to you
for a second?

04:05.946 --> 04:07.246
Yeah, babe.

04:07.248 --> 04:09.548
So, find us something really
good, and no Indian.

04:09.550 --> 04:10.716
Oh, hey, or Chinese.

04:10.718 --> 04:13.285
- I can't do Italian.
- I'm a no-go on sushi.

04:13.287 --> 04:16.121
I am so tired
of playing this game.

04:16.123 --> 04:18.023
We all know where we're going!

04:18.025 --> 04:19.258
Dre, what are we
gonna tell them?

04:19.260 --> 04:20.192
The truth.

04:20.194 --> 04:21.126
They're children.

04:21.128 --> 04:22.561
They're not just children, Bow.

04:22.563 --> 04:24.029
They're<i> Black</i> children.
Oh, boy.

04:24.031 --> 04:25.897
And they need to know the world
that they're living in.

04:25.899 --> 04:27.466
Come on, Bow.
Think.

04:27.468 --> 04:28.700
Dre, I'm not clueless here.

04:28.702 --> 04:30.736
All right, the twins
are just still so little.

04:30.738 --> 04:31.903
And I'm not ready for them

04:31.905 --> 04:33.105
to think and see the world
the way you do.

04:33.107 --> 04:34.473
I mean, come on.

04:34.475 --> 04:36.541
Jack still thinks that when
you swallow a piece of gum,

04:36.543 --> 04:38.810
it grows a gum tree
in your stomach.

04:38.812 --> 04:40.078
[ Chuckles ] Gum tree.

04:40.080 --> 04:42.481
Yeah.
Kids.

04:42.483 --> 04:45.250
But it does take seven years
for it to digest, right?

04:45.252 --> 04:47.419
Oh, my God.

04:47.421 --> 04:50.756
But that Pop Rocks kid,
he... he's dead, right, Bow?

04:50.758 --> 04:51.923
Man.

04:51.925 --> 04:53.325
I can't believe
these cops saying

04:53.327 --> 04:54.760
they thought this kid had a gun.

04:54.762 --> 04:58.096
Um, he actually
<i>did</i> have a gun, Pops.

04:58.098 --> 05:00.165
It wasn't loaded,
and it was in the trunk,

05:00.167 --> 05:01.600
but he did have one.

05:01.602 --> 05:03.468
Well, regardless,
those dirty cops

05:03.470 --> 05:05.504
still didn't have
no damn good reason

05:05.506 --> 05:07.139
to pull him over
in the first place.

05:07.141 --> 05:08.640
You mean other than the fact

05:08.642 --> 05:11.109
that he was driving
90 miles an hour?

05:11.111 --> 05:12.344
90? Pssh.

05:12.346 --> 05:13.845
I was driving 90 miles an hour

05:13.847 --> 05:15.480
with a gun in my trunk
last week.

05:15.482 --> 05:16.748
What's the point of being 25

05:16.750 --> 05:18.417
if you can't make
a few mistakes?

05:18.419 --> 05:19.751
He's 17.

05:19.753 --> 05:21.653
Pops, do you know
anything about this case?

05:21.655 --> 05:23.789
I'm old enough to know
when I'm hearing the same story

05:23.791 --> 05:24.923
told a different way.

05:24.925 --> 05:27.326
Police beating up
on an unarmed Black man...

05:27.328 --> 05:29.761
That's a story
I've been hearing all my life.

05:29.763 --> 05:30.762
Yeah.

05:30.764 --> 05:31.930
Coates says that the violence

05:31.932 --> 05:33.165
and police brutality
isn't new...

05:33.167 --> 05:34.433
It's just that the cameras are.

05:34.435 --> 05:35.634
Well, this fella Coates
sounds like

05:35.636 --> 05:37.102
he knows
what he's talking about.

05:37.104 --> 05:40.505
Now, hold up. I said the exact
same thing five minutes ago.

05:40.507 --> 05:42.708
Police are acting like
this is something new!

05:42.710 --> 05:46.278
The only thing new is that
people are recording this!

05:46.280 --> 05:47.779
I don't remember that.
You remember that?

05:47.781 --> 05:50.849
Yeah, it's not really
ringing a bell for me, Dad.

05:50.851 --> 05:52.317
Zoey, back me up!

05:52.319 --> 05:54.519
Dad, I'm trying to make sure
this P.F. Chang's menu

05:54.521 --> 05:55.620
doesn't get any traction.

05:55.622 --> 05:56.888
[ Groans ]

05:56.890 --> 05:59.291
Pops, all I'm saying is
the boy reads one book,

05:59.293 --> 06:02.394
and all of a sudden, he's
an expert on all things Black.

06:02.396 --> 06:04.730
Boy, you did the same thing
when you was his age.

06:04.732 --> 06:05.731
Or don't you remember

06:05.733 --> 06:07.399
"The Autobiography
of Malcolm X"?

06:07.401 --> 06:09.301
We didn't land on Plymouth Rock!

06:09.303 --> 06:11.103
Plymouth Rock landed on us!

06:12.639 --> 06:15.540
Malcolm X was a revolutionary.

06:15.542 --> 06:18.744
There would be no
Ta-Nehisi whatever his name is

06:18.746 --> 06:20.746
had there not been a Malcolm X!

06:20.748 --> 06:23.014
Well, there wouldn't be
no funny-named colored boys

06:23.016 --> 06:24.850
if it wasn't for good old
James Baldwin.

06:24.852 --> 06:26.485
He was talking about
the same stuff

06:26.487 --> 06:28.220
we're talking about now
50 years ago.

06:28.222 --> 06:29.588
Who's James Baldwin?

06:29.590 --> 06:30.922
Yeah, see?

06:30.924 --> 06:33.759
This is what not giving out
surprise ass-whoopings gets you,

06:33.761 --> 06:34.760
this right here.

06:34.762 --> 06:36.228
Listen, son.

06:36.230 --> 06:39.030
I'm glad to see that you're
taking an interest in the world

06:39.032 --> 06:42.033
and what's going on in it,
man, but just having

06:42.035 --> 06:45.170
a little knowledge
can be a dangerous thing.

06:45.172 --> 06:47.172
All right, you need
to take the time

06:47.174 --> 06:49.040
and get the full picture.

06:49.042 --> 06:50.876
All right,
this is serious stuff, son.

06:50.878 --> 06:53.678
Kids are dying in the street!

06:53.680 --> 06:55.847
Hold up.
Kids are dying?

06:55.849 --> 06:57.716
We're kids!

06:57.718 --> 06:59.885
[ Sighs ]

06:59.887 --> 07:01.620
Why is everybody
acting surprised

07:01.622 --> 07:03.422
that we can hear
the conversation?

07:03.424 --> 07:05.891
I mean, they're right there.

07:05.893 --> 07:07.692
Basically inches away.

07:07.694 --> 07:09.461
Zoey, can you take them
into the dining room

07:09.463 --> 07:10.729
and look at the menus in there?

07:10.731 --> 07:11.730
Sure.
Maybe we should just

07:11.732 --> 07:13.265
go look at them in the garage.

07:13.267 --> 07:15.133
All right, okay. Or how about
we go to a neighbor's house?

07:15.135 --> 07:17.936
That's as good a place as any
to pretend we can't hear things

07:17.938 --> 07:19.271
being shouted across the room.

07:19.273 --> 07:20.539
Okay.

07:20.541 --> 07:22.073
Go in there.

07:22.075 --> 07:24.376
Yeah.
Thank you.

07:24.378 --> 07:26.244
What are you guys doing?

07:26.246 --> 07:27.879
Here comes Rae Dawn Chong.

07:27.881 --> 07:30.882
Hey, can we please
not freak the kids out

07:30.884 --> 07:32.717
without giving justice
a chance to be served?

07:32.719 --> 07:34.152
And what's
that supposed to mean?

07:34.154 --> 07:37.556
Look, I know that a lot of stuff
has let us down recently,

07:37.558 --> 07:40.292
but the evidence in this case
is pretty clear.

07:40.294 --> 07:41.593
And?

07:41.595 --> 07:45.397
And maybe if we take a beat
and let the system work,

07:45.399 --> 07:47.432
we can hold off
on having to unpack

07:47.434 --> 07:49.935
all of this ugliness
for two kids that have

07:49.937 --> 07:52.337
plenty of time
to see all of that and more.

07:52.339 --> 07:54.239
Look, here, sweetheart,
you're my daughter-in-law,

07:54.241 --> 07:55.240
and you know I love you.

07:55.242 --> 07:56.274
I think you're just about

07:56.276 --> 07:57.676
the prettiest, smartest woman
I know.

07:57.678 --> 07:59.177
Thank you.
And I'm often at a loss

07:59.179 --> 08:00.579
as to why you married my son.

08:00.581 --> 08:02.848
I'm sure you had plenty of
offers... athletes, doctors.

08:02.850 --> 08:03.815
Pops.
There were like three.

08:03.817 --> 08:05.283
Were you trying
to get to something?

08:05.285 --> 08:07.452
Oh, yes. Bow, if you're asking
us to lie to Jack and Diane,

08:07.454 --> 08:09.354
I can't support you on that, darling.
Mnh-mnh.

08:09.356 --> 08:10.755
I'm not asking you
to lie to them.

08:10.757 --> 08:12.757
I just want to give them
a little faith in the world.

08:12.759 --> 08:15.093
You know, help them
hold on to their innocence

08:15.095 --> 08:17.095
and be kids
for a little while longer.

08:17.097 --> 08:20.198
[ Chuckles ] See, you want
to soft-pedal the real.

08:20.200 --> 08:22.434
I didn't soft-pedal the real
with you, Dre,

08:22.436 --> 08:24.936
and you turned out just fine.

08:24.938 --> 08:27.339
Ma, who's Jeffrey Dahmer?

08:29.376 --> 08:31.343
Ma, who's Lorena Bobbitt?

08:34.715 --> 08:37.482
Ma, who's Peabo Bryson?

08:37.484 --> 08:39.951
♪ I celebrate... ♪

08:41.321 --> 08:42.320
You're right.

08:42.322 --> 08:44.656
So we will do this
your way for now.

08:44.658 --> 08:49.327
Because Lord knows I did not
need to know about Peabo Bryson.

08:49.329 --> 08:51.897
Yeah.
Well, Peabo turns me on.

08:51.899 --> 08:54.900
[ Chuckles ]
It's all I'm saying.

08:54.902 --> 08:58.069
<i>It appears a decision about
the indictment has been made</i>

08:58.071 --> 08:59.538
<i>and is about to be announced.</i>

08:59.540 --> 09:01.406
What's an indictment?

09:01.408 --> 09:02.974
Well...
Oh, okay, well, listen.

09:02.976 --> 09:05.577
It seems as if some people that
were supposed to protect us

09:05.579 --> 09:06.745
didn't do the right thing.

09:06.747 --> 09:08.413
But it doesn't happen
very often.

09:08.415 --> 09:09.648
It happens all the time.

09:09.650 --> 09:12.317
It doesn't happen very often.

09:12.319 --> 09:13.585
But this time, it did.

09:13.587 --> 09:16.354
And if it did, then they're
gonna get in trouble.

09:16.356 --> 09:18.089
So, the cops are the bad guys?

09:18.091 --> 09:18.924
- Yes.
- No.

09:18.926 --> 09:21.159
No.
Some of them are.

09:21.161 --> 09:22.594
- It's a gray area.
- Yeah.

09:22.596 --> 09:23.695
Charcoal gray.

09:23.697 --> 09:24.829
Basically black.

09:24.831 --> 09:27.399
The point is that
if something bad happened,

09:27.401 --> 09:29.868
then that's why
we have laws and trials,

09:29.870 --> 09:32.571
and we just let
the justice system do its job.

09:32.573 --> 09:34.172
- Yeah.
- Come on, come on, come on.

09:34.174 --> 09:35.440
Lemon: <i>We take you now
to the courthouse.</i>

09:35.442 --> 09:36.741
Man:<i> Good evening.</i>

09:36.743 --> 09:38.577
<i>The grand jury has had a chance</i>

09:38.579 --> 09:40.779
<i>to review the case
and the evidence</i>

09:40.781 --> 09:42.447
<i>and have decided
against the idea</i>

09:42.449 --> 09:44.416
<i>that either the arguments...</i> -You've
got to be... -What the hell?!

09:44.418 --> 09:46.585
<i>Or the evidence supported
the filing of...</i> Come on!

09:46.587 --> 09:49.354
<i>Any criminal charges against any of the
officers in this...</i> Turn it off. Turn it off!

09:49.356 --> 09:53.458
Kids, this is your
justice system doing its job.

09:53.460 --> 09:54.626
Pops: Same old story.

09:54.628 --> 09:55.594
I don't understand.

09:55.596 --> 09:57.596
Yeah, how did this happen?

09:57.598 --> 09:59.631
[ Sighs ]

09:59.633 --> 10:03.401
And how did P.F. Chang's
get back in the mix?

10:03.403 --> 10:04.703
I thought I threw this away.

10:08.775 --> 10:10.709
♪ Won't you help to sing? ♪

10:10.711 --> 10:12.210
Dre:<i> Hope is what keeps us</i>

10:12.212 --> 10:14.746
<i>as a people and a country
moving forward.</i>

10:14.748 --> 10:17.382
<i>And, sadly, the best way
to end that movement</i>

10:17.384 --> 10:19.150
<i>is to take away that hope.</i>

10:19.152 --> 10:22.821
<i>That hope, at its core,
is all we really have</i>

10:22.823 --> 10:26.891
<i>to give our children,
a belief in something better.</i>

10:26.893 --> 10:29.494
♪ Redemption song ♪ <i>But when everything
around them is doing its best</i>

10:29.496 --> 10:33.098
<i>to squash that belief,
what do you do?</i>

10:33.100 --> 10:35.333
I cannot believe
this keeps happening.

10:35.335 --> 10:38.269
I can't believe you're
surprised it keeps happening.

10:38.271 --> 10:39.604
I know that this is bad.

10:39.606 --> 10:41.773
But, you guys, despite
its flaws, we still have

10:41.775 --> 10:43.742
the best justice system
in the whole world.

10:43.744 --> 10:46.144
We just have to have faith that
it's gonna work itself out.

10:46.146 --> 10:47.178
Yeah, right. Right.

10:47.180 --> 10:49.114
And... And... And...
And why should we

10:49.116 --> 10:50.315
listen to you, again, Bow?

10:50.317 --> 10:51.583
Because you just assured us

10:51.585 --> 10:53.685
that these men
would be brought to justice.

10:53.687 --> 10:56.154
Because I<i> hoped</i> that they would.

10:56.156 --> 10:59.324
Why, Bow? Wh-When has it ever
worked for us, huh?

10:59.326 --> 11:01.693
When do we ever get a win?

11:01.695 --> 11:02.861
How about O.J.?

11:02.863 --> 11:04.162
Oh, there it is.

11:04.164 --> 11:07.032
That's low even for you,
Rainbow.

11:07.034 --> 11:08.767
Dre: No, Ma, no. Not at all.

11:08.769 --> 11:11.436
You know, this is actually
a perfect example.

11:11.438 --> 11:14.439
It shows how Black people
were so desperate for a win

11:14.441 --> 11:16.608
that we had to root
for this idiot.

11:16.610 --> 11:19.044
Whoo! Before then, we
were 0-10 million.

11:19.046 --> 11:21.479
And, you know, let's not forget
that the glove didn't fit.

11:21.481 --> 11:22.614
- Exactly.
- Did not fit.

11:22.616 --> 11:23.782
- No!
- Yeah, but, no...

11:23.784 --> 11:26.117
I'm just trying,
for the sake of our children,

11:26.119 --> 11:27.485
to find a silver lining here.

11:27.487 --> 11:29.120
And you know what?
Let's not forget

11:29.122 --> 11:32.891
that statistically speaking,
the system works

11:32.893 --> 11:33.992
more than it doesn't.

11:33.994 --> 11:36.394
Well, according
to these statistics,

11:36.396 --> 11:39.564
25% of police shootings
in L.A. County

11:39.566 --> 11:43.301
from 2010 to 2014
were of unarmed suspects.

11:43.303 --> 11:46.204
What? The police are
shooting people with no arms?

11:46.206 --> 11:48.073
Why am I just now
hearing about this?

11:48.075 --> 11:51.810
No, Jack, "unarmed" means
he didn't have a weapon.

11:51.812 --> 11:53.912
Of course
he didn't have a weapon.

11:53.914 --> 11:54.913
He had no arms.

11:54.915 --> 11:56.414
[ All groaning ]

11:56.416 --> 11:59.084
You know, I-I got this one.
I got this one, guys.

11:59.086 --> 12:01.252
Jack, Jack.

12:01.254 --> 12:03.021
You ever think how lucky you are

12:03.023 --> 12:04.823
to be born
with two healthy arms?

12:04.825 --> 12:06.524
Yeah.
Okay.

12:06.526 --> 12:08.593
Can I just play Devil's Advocate
here for a second?

12:08.595 --> 12:11.429
Bow, why must you always
advocate for the Devil?

12:11.431 --> 12:13.998
He does not need help
with his legal team.

12:14.000 --> 12:16.234
Lucifer's
curly-haired lawyer.

12:16.236 --> 12:20.672
Okay, obviously I am
anti-police brutality.

12:20.674 --> 12:22.907
But that doesn't mean
I have to be anti-the-police.

12:22.909 --> 12:27.412
Look, 25% of these suspects
are unarmed, which is horrible.

12:27.414 --> 12:28.413
Mm-hmm.
But that means

12:28.415 --> 12:31.416
that 75% of them were armed.

12:31.418 --> 12:33.218
The police have to
deal with that every day.

12:33.220 --> 12:34.419
Oh, Lord.

12:34.421 --> 12:36.254
I guess what
you're saying makes sense,

12:36.256 --> 12:38.690
but isn't that their job, Mom?
Yeah.

12:38.692 --> 12:41.226
I mean, if you killed one out of
every four of your patients,

12:41.228 --> 12:43.094
wouldn't that make you
a pretty bad doctor?

12:43.096 --> 12:44.262
You mean she<i> doesn't</i> kill

12:44.264 --> 12:46.064
one out of every four
of her patients?

12:46.066 --> 12:48.099
Look here, my Daddy told me
every morning I left the house

12:48.101 --> 12:50.101
there's only two kind of people
you got to worry about...

12:50.103 --> 12:51.136
The police and thugs.

12:51.138 --> 12:52.470
I wasn't worried about
the thugs.

12:52.472 --> 12:53.772
Hell, I married one.

12:53.774 --> 12:57.609
Well, all I know is that I'm
still terrified of the police.

12:57.611 --> 13:01.079
Well, that's very interesting,
coming from a man

13:01.081 --> 13:03.114
who is on a first-name basis
with all the cops

13:03.116 --> 13:04.883
that patrol our neighborhood.

13:04.885 --> 13:05.650
Officer Joe?

13:05.652 --> 13:06.785
Officer Joe:<i> Speaking.</i>

13:06.787 --> 13:07.886
Hey, it's me... Dre.

13:07.888 --> 13:09.154
<i>What's wrong now, Dre?</i>

13:09.156 --> 13:10.121
I heard a noise.

13:10.123 --> 13:10.989
<i>Really? Again?</i>

13:10.991 --> 13:11.790
Yes, again.

13:11.792 --> 13:13.057
<i>[ Groans ] All right.</i>

13:13.059 --> 13:15.326
Could you come out here
and check it out?

13:15.328 --> 13:16.828
<i>Now?</i>
Just use your key.

13:16.830 --> 13:20.098
I have a sneaker collection
to protect.

13:20.100 --> 13:22.000
<i>And it looks like
we're getting word now</i>

13:22.002 --> 13:25.170
<i>of protests across the country
becoming violent.</i>

13:25.172 --> 13:28.273
<i>Reports of small fires
and looting in Los Angeles.</i>

13:28.275 --> 13:29.841
It's gonna be a long night.

13:29.843 --> 13:31.276
I'm gonna go get some food.

13:31.278 --> 13:33.611
I am assuming it is Chipotle.

13:33.613 --> 13:34.779
All: Yes.

13:34.781 --> 13:35.781
Uh-huh.

13:40.253 --> 13:41.586
Where's the Chipotle?

13:41.588 --> 13:43.254
I canceled the order.

13:43.256 --> 13:44.589
[ All grumbling ]

13:44.591 --> 13:46.591
All right,
listen, listen, listen.

13:46.593 --> 13:49.460
I heard on the radio it's
really getting bad out there.

13:49.462 --> 13:52.263
Now, trust me, I've been
in my share of riots, okay?

13:52.265 --> 13:54.499
And you don't want to be
eating Mexican food

13:54.501 --> 13:55.767
during a lockdown.

13:55.769 --> 13:58.703
Made that mistake during
the Lakers championship riot.

13:58.705 --> 14:02.273
You want bland-palate items
that keep the toilets moving,

14:02.275 --> 14:05.777
binding foods... rice,
government cheese...

14:05.779 --> 14:09.180
Vodka to drink
and to wash your hands with.

14:09.182 --> 14:10.849
Mm-hmm.
Yeah, I see all that over there.

14:10.851 --> 14:13.184
W-W-What's this?

14:13.186 --> 14:14.018
Riot cash.

14:14.020 --> 14:15.119
What?

14:15.121 --> 14:16.888
These are filled
with silver nickels

14:16.890 --> 14:20.124
and gold charm bracelets
from past lovers.

14:20.126 --> 14:23.695
Now, trust me, precious metals
and sexual favors

14:23.697 --> 14:26.698
are the only currency
during times of civil unrest.

14:27.868 --> 14:30.134
Damn, woman, I taught you well.

14:30.136 --> 14:31.569
[ Laughs ] You get the
rest of the stuff?

14:31.571 --> 14:32.837
Oh, yeah. In the trunk.

14:32.839 --> 14:33.838
[ Coin bags thud ]

14:33.840 --> 14:35.073
Kevlar vests.
Mm-hmm.

14:35.075 --> 14:36.241
Tear gas.
Mm-hmm.

14:36.243 --> 14:37.742
Hollow-tipped ammunition.
Mmm.

14:37.744 --> 14:40.545
I got nails and 2x4s
to secure the entrances.

14:40.547 --> 14:41.479
Outstanding.

14:41.481 --> 14:43.081
Now, don't get me wrong,
Rainbow.

14:43.083 --> 14:44.682
Part of me is hoping
folks come in here

14:44.684 --> 14:46.384
and steal some of this
hideous furniture.

14:46.386 --> 14:48.720
But I still got to
protect my grandkids.

14:48.722 --> 14:50.088
Junior: Turn it up, Dad.

14:50.090 --> 14:51.489
Who's this?

14:51.491 --> 14:53.258
Ta-Nehisi Coates.

14:53.260 --> 14:55.693
Coates: <i>The long history of
criminalizing Black people...</i> Oh.

14:55.695 --> 14:57.829
<i>In this country, which did
not begin with Eric Garner...</i>

14:57.831 --> 14:59.998
What's he saying? <i>...which did
not begin with Tamir Rice,</i>

15:00.000 --> 15:01.532
<i>which did not begin
with John Crawford.</i>

15:01.534 --> 15:03.501
<i>This is
a very, very old tradition.</i>

15:03.503 --> 15:05.336
Unbelievable.

15:05.338 --> 15:07.171
Where is CNN
when I'm saying that stuff?

15:07.173 --> 15:10.909
The same place Def Jam is when
you're rapping in the shower.

15:10.911 --> 15:12.510
♪ You think you dope, soap? ♪

15:12.512 --> 15:13.945
♪ You got no hope, soap ♪

15:13.947 --> 15:15.580
♪ Shampooing is what I'm doing ♪

15:15.582 --> 15:18.049
♪ You can't cope, nope ♪

15:18.051 --> 15:21.786
The point is, these protestors
have the right idea.

15:21.788 --> 15:23.254
You're right, Dad.

15:23.256 --> 15:24.889
- I'm going down there.
- What? No, you're not.

15:24.891 --> 15:26.591
- That's my boy.
- Hey, hey!

15:26.593 --> 15:28.559
You are not going anywhere.
Sit down.

15:28.561 --> 15:29.727
Oh, I see.

15:29.729 --> 15:31.429
Now that you got yourself
a little something,

15:31.431 --> 15:34.132
it's okay for other people's
children to go fight the battle,

15:34.134 --> 15:35.233
but not yours?

15:35.235 --> 15:36.434
Junior: Yeah, Dad.

15:36.436 --> 15:38.202
You're always telling me,
don't talk about it...

15:38.204 --> 15:39.037
Be about it.

15:39.039 --> 15:40.204
I'm trying to be about it.

15:40.206 --> 15:41.606
Stop using my quotes against me.

15:41.608 --> 15:43.708
In my day, when you wanted
to make change happen,

15:43.710 --> 15:44.809
you put your feet
to the pavement

15:44.811 --> 15:45.944
and you got yourself out there.

15:45.946 --> 15:47.245
Pops, please.

15:47.247 --> 15:49.814
The only place you got out
to was the speakeasy.

15:49.816 --> 15:51.883
What you talking about, Andre?
You know I was a Panther.

15:51.885 --> 15:53.251
You were a Bobcat.

15:53.253 --> 15:54.485
What's a Bobcat?

15:56.289 --> 15:57.755
We were Panther-adjacent,

15:57.757 --> 15:59.958
still part
of the radical cat family.

15:59.960 --> 16:02.226
It's just...
Look, the Panther uniform

16:02.228 --> 16:03.428
just wasn't conducive

16:03.430 --> 16:05.763
to Southern California
weather patterns.

16:05.765 --> 16:08.599
Shh, shh, shh.
The lawyer's speaking.

16:08.601 --> 16:11.069
<i>It's important in the midst
of all the public vilifying</i>

16:11.071 --> 16:13.104
<i>of the police department,
whose members acted</i>

16:13.106 --> 16:14.405
<i>completely within procedure,</i>

16:14.407 --> 16:16.274
<i>to remember Mr. McQuillan
was no angel.</i>

16:16.276 --> 16:17.675
- What?
- What does that mean?

16:17.677 --> 16:19.777
- I can't believe they said that.
- Why would they even say that?

16:19.779 --> 16:20.812
What does that even mean?

16:20.814 --> 16:22.080
They're talking about
somebody's child.

16:22.082 --> 16:24.248
That can easily be
one of these children here.

16:24.250 --> 16:25.683
That could have been one of us?

16:25.685 --> 16:26.918
Yes.
No, sweetie, no, no.

16:26.920 --> 16:28.419
Because if you get
stopped by the cops,

16:28.421 --> 16:30.822
you are gonna do
exactly what they say, okay?

16:30.824 --> 16:31.756
She's right.

16:31.758 --> 16:32.757
Listen to me.

16:32.759 --> 16:34.425
If you have to talk to the cops,

16:34.427 --> 16:36.761
there's only seven words
you need to know.

16:36.763 --> 16:37.595
"Yes, sir."

16:37.597 --> 16:38.429
"No, sir."

16:38.431 --> 16:39.697
And "Thank you, sir."

16:39.699 --> 16:40.598
Exactly.

16:40.600 --> 16:41.766
You make sure you live

16:41.768 --> 16:43.634
to fight your case in court,
you hear me?

16:43.636 --> 16:44.936
Bow! Mama!

16:44.938 --> 16:46.170
Enough!

16:46.172 --> 16:47.372
Wake up.

16:47.374 --> 16:50.842
Let's say they listen to
the cops and get in the car.

16:50.844 --> 16:52.176
Look what happened
to Freddie Gray.

16:52.178 --> 16:54.212
Yeah, and what if they make it
all the way to the station?

16:54.214 --> 16:55.680
Mm-hmm.
You remember Sandra Bland?

16:55.682 --> 16:57.548
And let's say
they do make it to trial.

16:57.550 --> 16:59.283
Mm-hmm.
You see where that gets us.

16:59.285 --> 17:00.785
Don't you get it, Bow?

17:00.787 --> 17:03.121
The system is rigged against us.

17:03.123 --> 17:04.555
Maybe it is, Dre.

17:04.557 --> 17:05.890
But I don't want to feel like

17:05.892 --> 17:08.026
my kids are living in a world

17:08.028 --> 17:12.030
that is so flawed that
they can't have any hope.

17:12.032 --> 17:14.499
Oh, so you want to
talk about hope, Bow?

17:14.501 --> 17:17.902
Obama ran on hope.

17:17.904 --> 17:22.740
Remember when he got elected,
and... and we felt like maybe,

17:22.742 --> 17:25.410
just maybe, we got out
of that bad place

17:25.412 --> 17:27.412
and made it to a good place?

17:27.414 --> 17:33.084
That the whole country was
really ready to turn the corner.

17:33.086 --> 17:35.253
You remember
that amazing feeling we had

17:35.255 --> 17:37.588
during the inauguration?

17:37.590 --> 17:40.258
I was sitting right next to you.

17:40.260 --> 17:43.394
And we were so proud.

17:43.396 --> 17:47.265
And we saw him
get out of that limo

17:47.267 --> 17:51.235
and walk alongside of it
and wave to that crowd.

17:51.237 --> 17:55.740
Tell me you weren't terrified
when you saw that.

17:55.742 --> 17:58.576
Tell me you weren't worried
that someone was gonna

17:58.578 --> 18:03.448
snatch that hope away from us
like they always do.

18:03.450 --> 18:08.519
That is the real world, Bow.

18:08.521 --> 18:10.721
And our children need to know

18:10.723 --> 18:13.391
that that's the world
that they live in.

18:13.393 --> 18:17.528
♪♪

18:17.530 --> 18:20.465
Come on.
Let's finish watching it.

18:20.467 --> 18:23.267
Let's see what
they're gonna say next.

18:23.269 --> 18:26.337
♪♪

18:37.150 --> 18:38.216
[ Clanging spoon ]
Rice is up!

18:38.218 --> 18:39.250
Come on, come on, come on.

18:39.252 --> 18:40.551
Let's go!

18:40.553 --> 18:41.919
Just plain rice?

18:41.921 --> 18:43.287
Yep.

18:43.289 --> 18:44.789
Can we at least
put some salt in it?

18:44.791 --> 18:47.458
Nope.
Salt is no good during a riot.

18:47.460 --> 18:48.426
Neither is butter.

18:48.428 --> 18:50.094
Now, here, take this vodka.

18:50.096 --> 18:51.629
Go wash your hands
before you eat.

18:51.631 --> 18:53.564
Ruby, you know we have other
food in the fridge, right?

18:53.566 --> 18:54.665
Maybe we can just...
Rainbow.

18:54.667 --> 18:56.434
Sit down and eat your rice.

18:56.436 --> 18:57.268
Okay.

18:57.270 --> 18:59.137
That food in the refrigerator

18:59.139 --> 19:01.572
is now part
of our weapons arsenal.

19:01.574 --> 19:02.607
Frozen fruit...

19:02.609 --> 19:03.441
[ Loud smack ]
Oh!

19:03.443 --> 19:04.575
Deadly.

19:04.577 --> 19:06.144
You don't want
to get hit upside the head

19:06.146 --> 19:08.279
with a frozen apple.

19:08.281 --> 19:09.814
It'll knock your block off.

19:09.816 --> 19:11.983
See this dent?
Granny Smith.

19:14.254 --> 19:15.753
I need you to cover for me.

19:15.755 --> 19:17.588
Cover for you?
Why?

19:17.590 --> 19:19.157
I'm going down to the protest.

19:19.159 --> 19:20.758
No, I'm not covering for that.

19:20.760 --> 19:21.826
Well, I'm going, so...

19:21.828 --> 19:23.194
Why?

19:23.196 --> 19:25.830
Tell me why you want
to go down there so bad.

19:25.832 --> 19:27.932
So you can end up
in the hospital?

19:27.934 --> 19:29.700
Or... Or worse,
get killed?

19:29.702 --> 19:32.670
Do you... Do you want our
parents up at that podium?

19:32.672 --> 19:34.305
This is insane!

19:34.307 --> 19:38.176
What is wrong
with all of you people?

19:46.786 --> 19:49.820
Okay, baby girl.
It's gonna be all right.

19:49.822 --> 19:51.322
Yeah, Zoey, I'm sorry.

19:51.324 --> 19:53.691
I didn't even realize
you cared like that.

19:53.693 --> 19:55.126
Of course I care.

19:55.128 --> 19:57.195
You're... You're my brother.

19:57.197 --> 19:59.630
And I care about
this stupid case, too.

19:59.632 --> 20:00.631
I know.

20:00.633 --> 20:05.736
Bow, what are you smiling about?

20:05.738 --> 20:09.207
I'm just so happy there's
some depth inside of her.

20:09.209 --> 20:10.908
I was worried.

20:10.910 --> 20:14.245
I was really, really worried.

20:14.247 --> 20:16.514
But you've been
texting all night.

20:16.516 --> 20:18.816
Yeah.
About this.

20:18.818 --> 20:19.984
I'm pretty sure I saw

20:19.986 --> 20:22.153
a "dying laughing"
and heart-eyes emoji.

20:22.155 --> 20:24.689
No, I mean, not all about this.

20:24.691 --> 20:26.424
But a lot.

20:26.426 --> 20:29.427
You think I don't care just
because I don't yell stuff out

20:29.429 --> 20:31.762
like everyone here does,
but I do.

20:31.764 --> 20:34.332
I... I'm just confused.

20:34.334 --> 20:35.566
I'm confused, too.

20:35.568 --> 20:37.835
That's what made me read
Coates in the first place.

20:37.837 --> 20:39.770
But I don't need some book
to tell me

20:39.772 --> 20:41.072
how I'm supposed to feel.

20:41.074 --> 20:45.042
I know what I feel, and...

20:45.044 --> 20:47.712
it's lost.

20:47.714 --> 20:52.116
This is my generation,
and these are kids our age.

20:52.118 --> 20:54.919
Point is, I care.

20:54.921 --> 20:57.088
I just don't know what to do.

20:57.090 --> 21:00.258
Zoey, that's why it's important
that we talk about it.

21:00.260 --> 21:02.093
Well, I don't want
to talk about it.

21:02.095 --> 21:03.561
What's the point?

21:03.563 --> 21:06.097
Everybody I love has been here,
talking about it all night,

21:06.099 --> 21:08.299
and none of you know
what the answer is.

21:09.435 --> 21:13.404
Honestly, I don't even know
what the point is sometimes.

21:13.406 --> 21:16.474
I just feel hopeless.

21:16.476 --> 21:21.078
But you're not going
to give up, right?

21:21.080 --> 21:24.615
Yeah. You're the only one
in this house we actually trust.

21:24.617 --> 21:26.217
- Excuse me?
- What?

21:26.219 --> 21:28.085
Sorry, everybody.

21:28.087 --> 21:30.888
I'm just keeping it real.

21:30.890 --> 21:34.325
If you give up,
who's gonna fix it for us?

21:34.327 --> 21:36.827
Okay, come here, babies.
Come on.

21:36.829 --> 21:39.397
Nobody's giving up, okay?

21:39.399 --> 21:41.399
All right, look.
Here's the deal.

21:41.401 --> 21:43.601
This is the world
that we live in.

21:43.603 --> 21:45.736
A whole lot of White,
a whole lot of Black,

21:45.738 --> 21:48.339
but mostly gray.

21:48.341 --> 21:51.442
But as a family, we're gonna
figure it out together.

21:51.444 --> 21:52.476
That's right.

21:52.478 --> 21:54.178
That's right.

21:54.180 --> 21:56.113
You know what?

21:56.115 --> 21:58.916
I think we should all
go down there together,

21:58.918 --> 22:00.117
as a family.

22:00.119 --> 22:02.420
Really?
Mm-hmm.

22:02.422 --> 22:05.256
You know, I-I...
I don't think the world

22:05.258 --> 22:10.928
is as broken as you do, Dre,
but something's got to change.

22:10.930 --> 22:13.597
It's scary, but I think
we should go down there.

22:13.599 --> 22:16.267
Let's go.

22:16.269 --> 22:19.136
And I'll never give up.

22:19.138 --> 22:20.938
You're right to only trust me.

22:20.940 --> 22:21.706
Hm.

22:21.708 --> 22:23.107
Hey, Ma?
Yeah?

22:23.109 --> 22:25.042
